<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-719-764  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 719 764.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  August 7 1990 v4 n27 p187(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft seeking bigger LAN share. (local area network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wylie, Margie.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (market share)Novell Inc. (market share).andO;Ticker:    MSFT; NOVL.andO;Product:   LAN Manager (Network management software) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Local Area NetworksMarket AnalysisMarketing StrategyPromotion of Product.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft Corp. is trying to wrest a portion of the LAN market from NovellInc., its smaller but successful rival, the old-fashioned way -- with lots ofmoney.andM;Microsoft officials briefed industry analysts last week about its plan tospend $16 million over the next year to bolster sales of its LAN Manager.andP;  Inaddition, $5 million will be spent buying technologies that extend OS/2 LANManager into other environments, including Macintosh, the company said.andM;Provo, Utah-based Novell holds an estimated 60 percent of the total personalcomputer networking market.andP;  Microsoft hopes to make LAN Manager, after twoyears on the market,  a more serious competitor for Novell's NetWare -- whichhas its own NetWare for Macintosh -- by bundling Macintosh networking intothe core LAN Manager product rather than relying on OEMs to provide itseparately.andM;Although Microsoft has not announced which company will supply a Mac server,industry insiders say that 3Com Corp. of Santa Clara, Calif., is the sure betwith its LAN Manager-based 3+Open for Macintosh.andP;  -- By Margie Wylie</TEXT></DOC>